Led by the non-profit GNOME Foundation, GNOME is an international project that creates a free, open, easy-to-use computer environment with first-class internationalization and accessibility. Built entirely from software as approved by the Free Software Foundation, GNOME provides all of the common tools users expect from a modern computing environment. GNOME components form the basic desktop environments on many operating systems, e.g., Oracle's Solaris, Red Hat Enterprise Linux, Canonical's Ubuntu, Debian, Fedora, Linux Mint and openSUSE.

GNOME also provides a flexible and powerful platform for desktop and mobile developers, and provides an umbrella for an entire ecosystem of related technologies. GNOME technologies have been adopted for consumer and vertical market by companies such as Endless Mobile, Amazon, TiVo, Nokia, TouchTunes, Garmin and TomTom.

The GNOME project have produced toolkits such as GTK+ and Clutter, The browser engine WebKitGTK+, Sound and media library GStreamer, D-Bus interprocess communication, Pango text layout and XML parser libxml2/libxslt.

Developers from the GNOME community also pushes forward and take active part in the development of the Linux Kernel, Systemd and Wayland. Commercial companies adopt the functionality-rich components of GNOME, as the free license allows use in commercial products at no cost. While useful for companies, GNOME is the result of collaboration between those companies and volunteers from the public who focus on creating software that is great and easy to use by everyone.

GUADEC is the primary congress for GNOME users, developers, foundation leaders, individuals, governments and businesses worldwide. It is held annually in cities around Europe, and brings attendees together to share their experiences and ideas for developing, using and deploying GNOME technologies.

GUADEC annualy attracts around 300 key software developers, press, users, businesses and government representatives each year. Presentations are given by leaders, spokespeople, volunteers and motivated developers on a range of topics including the future directions of the GNOME Project, Unix, GNU/Linux, Free and Open Source software, development techniques, cutting edge features and ideas on technology and culture.

GUADEC conferences are attended by professional software developers, engineering students and free and open source enthusiasts. Both men and women attend the conference and the average age is between 20-35.
The primary aims of the annual GUADEC conference are:
• Set the direction of the GNOME project for the coming year.
• Draw new developers and contributors to the project.
• Help corporate partners be involved in the project.
• Connect developers, corporate partners and governments.
• Showcase the latest GNOME technologies.

GUADEC is not just a software conference. People come together to meet collaborators from chat rooms and mailing lists, to network, to visit old friends and make new ones, and to have fun! The venue and program for GUADEC 2014 will reflect these important aspects and will include time for tourism, sports and experiencing local traditions.

Apart from GUADEC, the GNOME project organizes over a dozen hack-fests per year and the two conferences GNOME Summit, a small meeting of core developers in North America, and GNOME.Asia, a rapidly expanding annual event focusing on the growing number of Asian users and developers, set for Beijing in 2014.

Help us make this happen by becoming a sponsor

GUADEC sponsorship offers a wide variety of benefits, and encourages sponsors to become more deeply involved in the community. The opportunity also exists to combine sponsorship of both GUADEC and GNOME.Asia events at a reduced price. Please see the Sponsor Package section and Terms and Conditions for more details.
Past sponsors who help make GUADEC and continuing GNOME work possible include:
Meet key contributors
It's a unique opportunity to meet contributors, maintainers and users of one of the world's leading Free and Open Source technology platforms.
Influence future product direction.Sponsoring and attending GUADEC not only gives you advance information on the GNOME's plans for the coming year, but provides you a voice in shaping those plans.
Sponsorship provides you with promotion through visible advertising, technical presentations, and international press coverage. Contribute to the development of GNOME.
Access technical talent

Experienced and capable software developers from around the globe attend GUADEC. Sponsorship allows you to meet individuals, consultancies, and potential business partners who can help you achieve your technical goals.
Network with technology decision-makers
GUADEC attendees typically include individuals who are responsible for government purchasing, setting technical agendas at major corporations, determining academic work and research.
Encourage technology adoption
GUADEC has been a site for product launches, and can be a great place to encourage software developers to use new technologies.

Sponsorship packages
Terms and conditions
1. By submitting a completed sponsor application form, all sponsoring entities ("the sponsor") agree to these Terms and Conditions for GUADEC ("the conference").

2. Sponsorship applications are handled on a “first come-first served” basis. Sponsors should be committed to Free Software deployment and improvement, and supportive of the conference organizers' mission. The conference retains the right to reject sponsors that it deems inappropriate.

3. Sponsorship pledges cannot be processed without payment. All pledges must be in Euros (€) or US Dollars ($), or with respect to GNOME.Asia South Korea Won (₩), or other currency as agreed, and made payable to the organization designated by the GNOME Foundation. The sponsor will be contacted regarding details of the money transfer.
4. GNOME.Asia packages are subject to separate Terms and Conditions. For more details see: http://2013.gnome.asia/sponsorship

5. After written acceptance of the sponsor's application form by the conference, the sponsor must provide any further signed agreements and the sponsorship funds to the conference organizers within 30 days of receiving the conference sponsorship invoice.

6. Once the sponsor's application has been secured, the sponsor must provide logos, digital graphics and/or any other details as required (e.g., the sponsor's brand name, trademarks, etc) within 14 days. The sponsor grants to the conference the right and permission to use its name and/or logo for promotion of the event. Likewise the sponsor is granted the right and permission to use the conference name and/or logo for communications about the event.

7. Requested materials should reach the conference organizers by requested deadlines, or they may not be properly processed. Physical materials (banners, handouts, etc) should be provided by the sponsor at least 30 days in advance of the event.

8. For sponsorship packages that include the use of signage, please note that space may be limited. The conference will inform each sponsor of the maximum size or number of signs allowed. The conference will not be liable for damage or loss of sponsors’ properties by fire, theft, accident or any other cause, by negligence or otherwise or in case of force majeure.

9. The sponsor may not sublet, assign or apportion any part of the item(s) sponsored nor represent, advertise or distribute literature or materials for the products or services of any other firm or organization except as approved in writing by the conference.
10. To limit conference production costs, the conference organizers may limit the number of colors used to print sponsor logos and materials.

11. To minimize detritus, the conference may use electronic versions of inserts and advertisements. The sponsors will be notified in advance to be able to provide material that might be better suited to the medium used.

12. Repeat sponsor status and discount level will be determined by the the conference organizers. Eligible sponsors may claim only one discount. Repeat sponsors' discounts: a) 6% package discount is available to those organizations sponsoring at any level who have also sponsored the conference within the past 2 years, i.e., 2011 or 2012. b) A 10% discount is available for organizations who qualify for 6%, but who will this year increase their sponsorship package level, e.g., Silver in 2012 to Gold in 2013.
13. Any remaining funds from sponsorship money will be donated to the GNOME Foundation upon completion of the conference for the GNOME Foundation's general use.

14. Sponsorship is not limited to financial support but can also be in the form of material provisions, e.g., hardware, software, services, etc. Should your organization be interested in sponsoring in an arrangement not listed in this brochure, please feel free to contact the conference organizers to discuss your preferences: sponsors@guadec.org
